Definition
A Primary Key for a data frame is a column group of columns within that data frame whose values uniquely determine each row of the data frame.

For planes it is tailnum


planes |&gt; 
  count(tailnum) |&gt; 
  filter(n &gt; 1)

# A tibble: 0 × 2
# ℹ 2 variables: tailnum &lt;chr&gt;, n &lt;int&gt;



This count command shows that each row has a unique value of tailnum proving that it is a primary key

